{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"58412cd5-6131-41ab-9c0a-012a597a1629","content":"## CPU Baseline Requirement Change\n\n**.NET 9 raised the x86-64 baseline** to require **SSE4.2, SSSE3, SSE4.1, and POPCNT** instructions. If you were already on .NET 10, your hardware passed that bar. **.NET 11 likely raises the baseline further** (to **AVX2**, introduced with Intel Haswell in 2013 / AMD Excavator in 2015).\n\nYour **2012-era x86 hardware** is probably Sandy Bridge or Ivy Bridge — those have AVX but **not AVX2**, which triggers the error at startup.\n\n### Your other platforms are fine:\n- **Windows Arm64 (SQ1)** — separate Arm64 baseline; unaffected.\n- **Raspberry Pi 4 (linux-arm64)** — separate Arm64 baseline; unaffected.\n\n### Options:\n1. **Retire the pre-2013 nodes** — replace with Haswell-era or newer hardware.\n2. **Stay on .NET 10 (LTS)** for those specific nodes while upgrading the rest of your fleet.\n3. Check the .NET 11 release notes for any **compat switch** (e.g., `DOTNET_EnableAVX2=0`), though baseline requirements are typically hard — the JIT and runtime internals depend on them.\n\n**TL;DR:** .NET periodically raises the minimum CPU instruction set. Your 2012 hardware no longer meets the new x86-64 floor.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1f2eb1f9-5405-44b2-bea8-910603f94dba","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET's hardware requirements, so I can answer directly.\n\nThe key issue: Starting with .NET 9, and more relevantly for their upgrade path, .NET has been raising the baseline CPU requirements for x86-64. Specifically:\n\n- .NET 8 and earlier: x86-64 baseline (no specific SIMD requirements beyond SSE/SSE2)\n- .NET 9+: The runtime started requiring certain instruction sets as baseline\n\nActually, let me think more carefully. The specific change that's most relevant:\n\n\nIn .NET 9, Microsoft raised the x86-64 baseline to require SSE4.2 and related instructions like SSSE3, SSE4.1, and POPCNT. If they were running .NET 10 successfully, they should already have SSE4.2 support, so the issue might be something else—either the baseline changed again between .NET 10 and .NET 11, or there's a different instruction set requirement being enforced now. .NET 11 might raise the baseline further to require AVX or AVX2, which would explain why 2012 hardware passes .NET 10 but fails on .NET 11. Since .NET 11 hasn't released yet, I'm speculating based on Microsoft's trajectory of progressively raising CPU baselines with each major version. Hardware baseline requirements in .NET are hard constraints that can't be disabled with environment variables or compatibility switches—the only real options are using older hardware that meets the baseline, sticking with an earlier .NET version, or checking if there's a compatibility mode available. I should also consider other platforms like Windows Arm64 to give a complete picture.","outputTokens":1567,"requestId":"B819:1F50C6:18187DC:1B1647C:69FD405C"},"id":"b5823f72-60e1-443d-81ba-e2657dc7e967","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:46:40.818Z","parentId":"20829afc-b948-45f9-b6d6-f92e86d7c3ee"}
